{"id":"1801.04944","submitter":"Paz Beniamini Dr.","authors":"Paz Beniamini, Rodolfo Barniol Duran, Dimitrios Giannios","title":"Marginally fast cooling synchrotron models for prompt GRBs","comments":"11 pages, 2 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1093/mnras/sty340","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph.HE","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Previous studies have considered synchrotron as the emission mechanism for\nprompt Gamma-Ray Bursts (GRBs). These works have shown that the electrons must\ncool on a timescale comparable to the dynamic time at the source in order to\nsatisfy spectral constraints while maintaining high radiative efficiency. We\nfocus on conditions where synchrotron cooling is balanced by a continuous\nsource of heating, and in which these constraints are naturally satisfied.\nAssuming that a majority of the electrons in the emitting region are\ncontributing to the observed peak, we find that the energy per electron has to\nbe $E\\gtrsim 20$ GeV and that the Lorentz factor of the emitting material has\nto be very large $10^3\\lesssim \\Gamma_{\\rm em} \\lesssim 10^4$, well in excess\nof the bulk Lorentz factor of the jet inferred from GRB afterglows. A number of\nindependent constraints then indicate that the emitters must be moving\nrelativistically, with $\\Gamma'\\approx 10$, relative to the bulk frame of the\njet and that the jet must be highly magnetized upstream of the emission region,\n$\\sigma_{\\rm up}\\gtrsim 30$. The emission radius is also strongly constrained\nin this model to $R\\gtrsim 10^{16}$cm. These values are consistent with\nmagnetic jet models where the dissipation is driven by magnetic reconnection\nthat takes place far away from the base of the jet.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 15 Jan 2018 19:00:17 GMT"}],"update_date":"2018-02-28"}
